<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="SimpleMauiApp._3section">
    <ScrollView>
        <VerticalStackLayout>
            <!-- Chapter Title -->
            <Label 
                Text="Types of Operating Systems - Detailed View"
                FontSize="24"
                FontAttributes="Bold"
                HorizontalOptions="Center"
                Margin="10" />

            <!-- Introduction -->
            <Label 
                Text="Operating Systems serve as the backbone of computing devices. Here’s a detailed exploration of the various types and their applications:"
                FontSize="16"
                Margin="10" 
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Center" />

            <!-- Batch Operating System -->
            <Label 
                Text="1. Batch Operating System"
                FontSize="18"
                FontAttributes="Bold"
                Margin="10" />
            <Label 
                Text="In a Batch OS, similar jobs are grouped together in batches and executed sequentially. These systems were commonly used in early mainframe computers. Users submit jobs, and the system executes them without direct user interaction."
                FontSize="16"
                Margin="10"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Start" />
            <Label 
                Text="Example: IBM’s early batch processing systems."
                FontSize="14"
                Margin="10"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Start" />

            <!-- Time-Sharing Operating System -->
            <Label 
                Text="2. Time-Sharing Operating System"
                FontSize="18"
                FontAttributes="Bold"
                Margin="10" />
            <Label 
                Text="Time-sharing systems allow multiple users to share system resources simultaneously. The CPU's time is divided among users, giving the illusion of direct interaction with the machine."
                FontSize="16"
                Margin="10"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Start" />
            <Label 
                Text="Example: UNIX systems in the 1970s."
                FontSize="14"
                Margin="10"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Start" />

            <!-- Distributed Operating System -->
            <Label 
                Text="3. Distributed Operating System"
                FontSize="18"
                FontAttributes="Bold"
                Margin="10" />
            <Label 
                Text="A Distributed OS manages a collection of independent computers and makes them appear as a single system to users. This type of OS is designed for systems that work collaboratively over a network."
                FontSize="16"
                Margin="10"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Start" />
            <Label 
                Text="Example: Google’s distributed systems for cloud computing."
                FontSize="14"
                Margin="10"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Start" />

            <!-- Real-Time Operating System -->
            <Label 
                Text="4. Real-Time Operating System (RTOS)"
                FontSize="18"
                FontAttributes="Bold"
                Margin="10" />
            <Label 
                Text="RTOS is used in applications requiring immediate responses, such as embedded systems, medical equipment, and automotive systems. These systems prioritize tasks to ensure timely execution."
                FontSize="16"
                Margin="10"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Start" />
            <Label 
                Text="Example: VxWorks used in aerospace and defense."
                FontSize="14"
                Margin="10"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Start" />

            <!-- Mobile Operating System -->
            <Label 
                Text="5. Mobile Operating System"
                FontSize="18"
                FontAttributes="Bold"
                Margin="10" />
            <Label 
                Text="Mobile OSs are optimized for touch-screen devices and power efficiency. They enable mobile devices to run apps, connect to the internet, and interact with hardware like cameras and GPS."
                FontSize="16"
                Margin="10"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Start" />
            <Label 
                Text="Examples: Android, iOS."
                FontSize="14"
                Margin="10"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Start" />

            <!-- Summary -->
            <Label 
                Text="Understanding the different types of Operating Systems and their use cases provides a solid foundation for exploring more advanced topics like OS architecture, kernel design, and virtualization."
                FontSize="16"
                Margin="10" 
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Center" />

            <!-- Next Button -->
            <Button
                Text="Next Chapter"
                BackgroundColor="Blue"
                TextColor="White"
                FontAttributes="Bold"
                HorizontalOptions="Center"
                VerticalOptions="End"
                Margin="10"
                Clicked="NextClicked" />
        </VerticalStackLayout>
    </ScrollView>
</ContentPage>